#Approach:

Approach:
Ye problem stack se solve hoti hai using LIFO concept.

1. String ko left se right traverse karte hain.
2. Agar opening bracket mile ( ( { [ ), to stack me push kar do.
3. Agar closing bracket mile:
   - Agar stack empty hai → koi matching opening nahi → return 0.
   - Stack se top pop karo aur check karo ki matching pair hai ya nahi.
   - Agar matching nahi hai → return 0.
4. Loop ke end me:
   - Agar stack empty hai → sab brackets balanced → return 1.
   - Agar stack empty nahi hai → kuch opening brackets bach gaye → return 0.

Main idea:
Har closing bracket ko uske nearest opening bracket se match karna hota hai,
isliye stack use karte hain (Last opened → First close).

Time Complexity: O(n)
Space Complexity: O(n)

#Code:

import java.util.Deque;
import java.util.ArrayDeque;

public class Solution {
    public int isBalanced(String A) {
        //You can code here

        Deque<Character> stack = new ArrayDeque<>();
        for(int i=0; i<A.length(); i++){
          char ch = A.charAt(i);

          if(ch == '(' || ch == '{' || ch == '['){
            stack.push(ch);
          }
          else{
            if(stack.isEmpty()) return 0;

            char opening = stack.pop();
            if((ch == ')' && opening == '(') || (ch == '}' && opening == '{') || (ch == ']' && opening == '[')){
              continue;
            }
            else{
              return 0;
            }
          }
        }
        if(stack.isEmpty()){
          return 1;
        }else{
          return 0;
        }
    }
}
